Enum Constant Detail

DEFAULTIO

public static final DioScanOption DEFAULTIO
Transfers data based on the the board type and sampling speed. This mode is used when no transfer mode is specified.

SINGLEIO

public static final DioScanOption SINGLEIO
Transfers one packet of data at a time. Each packet can contain multiple data samples, but only one sample from each channel. The sample rate is system dependent.

BLOCKIO

public static final DioScanOption BLOCKIO
Transfers data in blocks. Not recommended for slow acquisition rates, as the operation status is not available until one packet of data is collected (typically 512 samples).

BURSTIO

public static final DioScanOption BURSTIO
Transfers data from the FIFO after the scan completes. Allows maximum rates for finite scans up to the full capacity of the FIFO.

CONTINUOUS

public static final DioScanOption CONTINUOUS
Scans data in an endless loop. Once the required number of samples are acquired, the buffer is reset and the operation begins again. Call stopBackground to stop the operation.

EXTCLOCK

public static final DioScanOption EXTCLOCK
Data conversions are controlled by an external clock signal. Each conversion is triggered on the appropriate edge of the clock input signal. The rate parameter is usually ignored. The sampling rate is dependent on the clock signal. If no mode is specified, the mode which allows the maximum conversion rate is used.

For some devices, an approximation of the rate is used to determine the packet size. Set the rate parameter to an approximate maximum value. SingleIo is recommended for slow external clock rates; if the external clock rate is very slow (for example < 200 Hz) and the device supports BLOCKIO, include the SINGLEIO option.

EXTTRIGGER

public static final DioScanOption EXTTRIGGER
Sampling begins when a trigger condition is met. The trigger condition is programmable on some devices; refer to setTrigger Other devices only support "polled gate" triggering.

Assuming active high operation, data acquisition begins immediately if the trigger input is high. If the trigger input is low, acquisition is delayed until it goes high, and continues until the requested number of samples are taken, regardless of the state of the trigger input.
This option is useful if the signal is a pulse with a very low duty cycle, for example when the trigger signal is in a TTL low state most of the time, so that triggering is held off until the pulse occurs.

RETRIGGER

public static final DioScanOption RETRIGGER
Re-arms the trigger after a trigger event is performed. The scan begins when a trigger event occurs. When the scan completes, the trigger is re-armed to acquire the next batch of data. Use with the Continuous option to continue arming the trigger until stopBackground is called.

Use the setTrigger retriggerCount parameter to specify the number of samples to acquire with each trigger event. If you specify a trigger count that is either zero or greater than the value of the dInScan samplesPerPort parameter, the trigger count is set to the value of samplesPerPort.

Specify the Continuous option with the trigger count set to zero to fill the buffer with samplesPerChan samples, re-arm the trigger, and refill the buffer upon the next trigger.
